      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a104764d1521e4af",
      "text": "[[Screen]] is a full-screen window manager that multiplexes a physical terminal between several processes, typically interactive shells. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e77cf7e47c3ed779",
      "text": "# Using Screen with Livecode"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1dc7f2f8fb3a022b",
      "text": "The reason to use screen is so that you can run a long standing command in the background, without the shell() function just hanging and blocking. You can call something like:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "id": "9119fabe77bf52c7",
      "text": "screen -dmS fedwiki wiki"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ba6244a29b948d40",
      "text": "First is the d option, in conjunction with the m option. The dm option simply causes your screen to \"launch into the background,\" if you will  - [http://forums.steampowered.com/forums/showthread.php?t=427146 steampowered.com]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f9c7c697955bca08",
      "text": " It means your screen will be \"detached\" instead of showing the screen when you type the command. You can omit this option if you aren't sure if the server will run (like when you're debugging) to show the screen as soon as it starts. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f4b277d732bb43fa",
      "text": "This also means that if Screen itself hasn't been started already, it will be, then the command will be added to a new screen."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e6642e9e59489e53",
      "text": "Next is the S option. This option is basically a \"vanity\" option. When you create a new screen, it is automatically assigned a \"title\" such as \"pts-1,\" \"pts-2,\" etc. This can be confusing. the S option is used to set your own \"title\" (more on this in a second) to your screen, making things easier to remember."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "63d5cae8948e76ab",
      "text": "Next is the title. This is very simply an easy-to-remember name for the screen you are creating. It can be any string of characters, except spaces, with some exceptions, though a good rule is to use words seperated by underscores (_) or dashes/hyphens (-). "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "aeda06a25c972f84",
      "text": "Lastly is the command. This should be obvious if you already have your server running. (Screen is, after all, more or less your last step.)"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "id": "4ba9943af661e93b",
      "text": "screen -list"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4c0bc1d30e44b68a",
      "text": "This will return something like:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "id": "af2ed217582f5b2a",
      "text": "There are screens on:\n               9999.counter-strike (Detached)\n1 Sockets in /tmp/uscreens/S-user."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8e19b6a0f78876fc",
      "text": "It will look a little different. 9999 is the numeric identifier. This will generally change each time you make a new screen, and will certainly be different for you than \"9999.\" Then \"counter-strike\" is the title you assigned to the screen before. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fc33b345c9cd3696",
      "text": "To connect to a given screen, you use the r option."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "id": "9baca71bff2e8e90",
      "text": "screen -r identifier"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "069d2c3cb96404a8",
      "text": "This is how supposed to prevent \"session killing\". Need to investigate what bash is doing here:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "id": "a2478cb95de31f72",
      "text": "screen -dmS test bash -c 'echo waiting 5 senconds...; sleep 5; exec bash'"
    },
